            "body": "> If you don't want to have the verbose escaping of dot characters, you could also opt to use glob patterns and then match with `return vim.glob.to_lpeg(pattern):match(name) ~= nil`.\n> \n\nYes `vim.glob.to_lpeg` is what I was looking for! \n\n> But isn't this what [`root_dir`](https://neovim.io/doc/user/lsp.html#vim.lsp.Config) is for? Or are you suggesting that glob patterns are so widely used that `root_markers` should also support them?\n\nI think `root_dir` might be a little bit overkill for this simple use case, that can be easily supported by passing a simpler callback to `root_markers`, but it's not documented. So should it be documented or there's a purpose that I cannot grasp? (As for now 28 LSPs use wildcards)",
